\begin_layout Standard
(4) Now an econometrician that know microeconomics comes to the help of
 the statistician and notices the following, we cannot get demand price
 elasticities from market data because these quantities and prices are the
 result of the intersection of supply and demand.
 In order to estimate the demand function we need a demand shifter! Provide
 an example of a demand shifter 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}^{d}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the following 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(p_{t},z_{t}^{d})\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(u_{t}z_{t}^{d})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Show that the structural estimator is a consistent estimator of the elasticity
 of interest 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{IV}=\frac{cov(x_{t},z_{t}^{d})}{cov(p_{t},z_{t}^{d})}=\alpha_{1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(z_{t}^{d},x_{t})=\alpha_{1}cov(z_{t}^{d},p_{t})+cov(z_{t}^{d},u_{t})$
\end_inset

 from the equation of demand, under the assumptions we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and this is well-defined.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

